Bayrd Still Papers

Contents

Series I: Subject, Historical Reference, and Personal Files, 1933-1988

Scope and Contents

Series I materials reflect Still's professional and personal involvement with NYU and New York City.

Subseries A: Subject Files, 1937-1979

Scope and Contents

Subseries A: Subject Files covers Still's work with other historians and includes materials on conferences, talks, interviews, and other special events; projects such as the Albert Gallatin Papers Project; and Still's duties at New York University.

Subseries B: Historical Reference Files, 1933-1988

Scope and Contents

Subseries B: Historical Reference Files contains Still's research on the history of New York University and its relationship to New York City. It is missing a number of folders that were noted in the original inventory of the collection provided to the University Archives by Still.

Subseries C: Sources about Urbanism and Urban Development

Scope and Contents

Subseries C: Sources about Urbanism and Urban Development contains urban history research material that includes some original material, some published sources, and some of Still's own translations of published material. Materials contain published and unpublished sources about urbanism and urban development in the United States from the 17th century to the 20th century.

Series VI: Landmarks, 1957-1983

Scope and Contents

Series VI contains correspondence, articles, press releases, reports, minutes, and calendars concerning the landmarks marking project of the New York Community Trust, the Committee for the Preservation of Structures of Historical and Esthetic Importance, and the Landmarks Preservation Commission. Most of the correspondence is between Still and Ralph Hayes, the executive director of New York Community Trust. Additional correspondence includes letters from the graduate fellows, which closed to researchers.

Photos from two reports regarding United State Presidents and United States Vice-Presidents were separated and added to the University Archives photo collection.

Scope and Contents

This series is comprised of four boxes containing 47 copper engravings individually mounted on wood blocks. Prints created from these engravings were included in Still's book, Mirror for Gotham, which was published by New York University Press in 1956.
